You need to make the 'thing', whatever that may be, findable. You can't measure or monitor something if you can't find (or share) it. 

In a technological system, you can use a few mechanisms to find or return to something: 
- search
 - properties 
 - links 
 - folders
 - tags
 - bookmarks 

So what do you do? Make a record of it. 

Take a photo, record a voice note, capture your thought in a Daily Note. The thing needs to exist somewhere outside of your brain, it needs to go from [[tacit knowledge\|tacit knowledge]] to [[concrete knowledge\|concrete knowledge]] otherwise how will you ever find it? Or monitor, remix, etc it? 

An imperfect record i[[Learn in Public/Think/Personal Knowledge Management allows you to organise and integrate thoughts and files\|Personal Knowledge Management allows you to organise and integrate thoughts and files]]se and integrate thoughts and files]], that would mean your thoughts and artefacts are easier to find. 

To record something for others, you can: 
- share your info / projects with others / a team 
- publish your notes (easy via Obsidian)
- share a 'changelog' of most recent notes you've worked on 
- share a TodayILearned publicly 
- [[Document, don't create\|Document, don't create]]

Side note: archaeology is basically discovering intentional and unintentional records of humanity's past, but they have to find them first. 

Concept first encountered in [[Learn in Public/Reference/Van Der Hoeven (2024) Learning In Public With Personal Knowledge Management\|Van Der Hoeven (2024) Learning In Public With Personal Knowledge Management]]
